Team-based software projects are a core component of programming education, yet evaluating how well students collaborate remains difficult. Instructors typically rely on manual inspection of Git repositories, a process that scales poorly and introduces inconsistency when applied across hundreds of teams.

This paper presents Harmonia, a standalone web application that automatically retrieves Git repository data from the Artemis learning management platform and computes a Collaboration Quality Index (CQI) for each team. The CQI is a weighted composite of four sub-scores, namely LLM-rated effort balance, lines of code balance, file ownership spread, and temporal spread, designed to capture both the quantity and semantic quality of individual contributions. Harmonia presents these metrics in a centralized dashboard that enables instructors to identify problematic teams, compare collaboration patterns across the course, and access commit-level evidence for grading decisions.

In addition, this paper introduces a complementary student-facing feedback system integrated into the Athena assessment platform of Artemis. This system provides on-demand, non-graded code quality feedback categorized into four priority tiers, delivered both as an aggregated summary and as inline annotations within the development environment. By framing feedback as pedagogical guidance rather than evaluation, the system encourages students to seek critique early and often throughout the project.

We evaluate Harmonia through a manual assessment of five student teams, comparing its automated scores with independent human judgments across effort, complexity, and novelty dimensions. Inter-rater reliability between the two human reviewers exceeds 70% across all teams, and Harmonia's relative scoring patterns align with human assessments, though within a narrower range. We discuss current limitations, including analysis runtime and the model's tendency to overestimate the significance of low-effort commits, and outline directions for future work.